photo.description: Bookplate of Samuel Weiller Fernberger (1887-1956) Samuel Weiller Fernberger (1887-1956) received his Ph.D. in psychology from the University of Pennsylvania in 1912 and was a member of the faculty at Clark University from 1912 until his death. F. W. Irwin wrote in Fernberger's obituary in The American Journal of Psychology, Vol. 69.4 (1956), p. 677-678: "At all stages of his career he exhibited an interest in those applications of experimental psychology that employed rigorous, preferably psychophysical, methods. He once testified before the Public Service Commission of Pennsylvania as an expert for the complainant in an action brought by the Yellow Cab Company of Philadelphia to prevent the use by others of taxicabs with colors alleged to resemble too closely the color of Yellow Cabs. His testimony involved not only verbal opinions but also the performance of demonstrations in the hearing room in the presence of the examiner and the interested parties. He mixed colors on a rotary color mixer to match the colors of the complainant's and respondent's cabs, showed that they were closely similar -- they differed by not more than three just noticeable differences along the base of a model of the color solid that was also produced -- and that their resemblance increased as the illumination of the room was decreased." Shortly before his death Fernberger donated a collection of psychological books and journals to the University of Pennsylvania as the Samuel W. Fernberger Collection of Psychology. Established heading: Fernberger, Samuel Weiller, 1887-1956 Other examples of Samuel Weiller Fernberger provenance Penn Libraries call number: FC6 D4538 641m 1644 All images from this book

photo.description: Bookplate of George Dunn (1864-1912), English bibliographer and book collector. From his obituary: On Tuesday of last week there died suddenly from pneumonia, at the age of forty-seven, a man whose remarkable gifts and attainments deserve more than the few paragraphs of record that have appeared in the public press. Mr. George Dunn, of Woolley Hall, near Maidenhead, was a member of a well-known Northumbrian Catholic family. He was educated at Beaumont College, Windsor, and at Stonyhurst, and was afterwards called to the Bar, though he never practised as a barrister. Inheriting from his father, the late George Dunn, of Bath House, Newcastle, large estates both in Northumberland and Berkshire, together with sufficient revenues, he was able to indulge the tastes of a scholar and collector of early printed books, mediaeval bindings, manuscripts, old silver, and old clocks, as well as those of a sportsman and keen angler, an astronomer and a student of forestry. Of none of these things was he content to have a superficial knowledge. Indeed, it may be said that he handled nothing without mastering it completely ... With these and other interests and pursuits George Dunn lived a tranquil and sequestered life, unmarried and alone in a large house, where he occasionally entertained one or other of the small band of intimates to whom he was devoted and by whom he was beloved. Neatly dressed, shy, spare, and rather below the middle height, he might sometimes be seen entering the British Museum or the Bodleian Library, or quietly turning over the book-treasures in the London sale rooms. But he never attended meetings or went into society, or gave the smallest encouragement to mere acquaintances. He was a Conservative in politics, a model landlord, and a loyal son of the Catholic Church. -- "Mr. George Dunn," The Times (11 March 1912), p. 11, issue 39843, col C. Established heading: Dunn, George, 1864-1912 Penn Libraries call number: Inc N-10 All images from this book

photo.description: ellenbog 1[4]93 kalb [Dated 15th-century autograph of Nikolaus Ellenbog (1481-1543), German humanist and theologian. Son of the physician and humanist Ulrich Ellenbog of Memmingen, Nikolaus studied at Heidelberg, Cracow and Montpellier before entering the Benedictine abbey of Ottobeuren in 1504. He served in various offices there, including prior, cellarer and novice master, and oversaw the operation of the abbey's printing press. He carried on a lively and well-preserved correspondence with other European humanists, including Erasmus (of course). Cf. his entry in P.G. Bietenholz and T.B. Deutscher, Contemporaries of Erasmus (Toronto: U of Toronto Press, 1985-1987), v. 1, p. 428, and in F. Posset, Renaissance Monks (Leiden: Brill, 2005), p. 155ff. The work in which this autograph appears, Johannes Melber's Vocabularius praedicantium (Augsburg: Anton Sorg, 20 May 1489), was probably one of Ellenbog's schoolbooks. (The note "kalb" likely refers to the compiler of the Vocabularius, Jodocus Eichmann de Kalb.) Established heading: Ellenbog, Nikolaus, 1481-1543 Established heading: Eichmann, Jodocus, 1420?-1491] Penn Libraries call number: Inc M-467 All images from this book Penn Libraries catalog record
